{panel:bgColor=#eae6ff}
*How will an ER be assessed?*
{panel}

{panel:bgColor=#deebff}
The problem (or opportunity) will be assessed and the outcomes sought will be used to guide the development of solutions that meet the stated objectives (‘To Be’).
{panel}

# There are likely to be multiple solution options and solutions can be a composite of system, process and people changes to solve a problem.
# Consideration will be given to the delivery of a solution (e.g. can the delivery be broken down into smaller components to enable faster realization of benefits?
# Can a Minimum Viable Product (MVP) be delivered that meets some of the business objectives and can evolve in to a more complete solution once it is operational and its effectiveness evaluated?)

{panel:bgColor=#deebff}
The rationale will be used to guide decisions on what solution will deliver the best value to the organization.
{panel}

# This is the cost:benefit analysis required to ensure that a solution is chosen that is not over-engineered and is ‘fit for purpose’.

{panel:bgColor=#deebff}
The measures of success will be defined and agreed review checkpoints will be put in place to track progress towards achieving the benefits of delivering the ER.
{panel}

# This approach will allow reviews to take place and adjustments to be made in future if the benefits are not being realized.

column522:
{panel:bgColor=#e3fcef}
What is the business problem (or opportunity) we are trying to address?
{panel}

#  There must be a clear business objective for requesting the ER.
# Solving the problem or pursuing the opportunity must demonstrate a tangible benefit to the organization.
# The business problem (or opportunity) is not a solution statement.  There could be multiple options to solving the problem or pursuing the opportunity.  Specifying a solution without exploring options can result in delivering an outcome that does not meet the business objectives.



{panel:bgColor=#e3fcef}
What is the rationale for solving the problem (or pursuing the opportunity)?
{panel}

# Do we understand the scope of the problem (or opportunity) and the impact on business performance?  This could include efficiency, cost, revenue, cashflow, legal & compliance impacts.
# How systemic is the problem (e.g. does it occur frequently / infrequently, does it impact a small number of files or most files, does it impact a small group of stakeholders or the whole organization?)
# If we do not know this and cannot quantify the impact the problem (or opportunity) has on the organization, this information is required to support a decision on whether to proceed with the ER.



{panel:bgColor=#e3fcef}
How will we ensure that the enhancement addresses the business problem (or opportunity)?
{panel}

# Do we understand the current state (‘As Is’) of the business function(s) impacted by the problem (or opportunity)?  If not, this is required to form the baseline for solution option development.
# Do we understand what success looks like?  How will we measure that the objective(s) of the ER have been met?  This is important in being able to demonstrate a commitment to achieving the benefits claimed in undertaking the ER.

